A central algorithm (SAGE) then assigns each student a single seat based on priority criteria (such as special needs inclusion, siblings at the school, and children of school staff) and conducts lotteries for oversubscribed schools ([registrocivil.rionegro.gov.ar](https://registrocivil.rionegro.gov.ar/articulo/13500/el-lunes-comienza-la-inscripcion-de-estudiantes-para-el-periodo-escolar-2016#:~:text=1,ninguno%20de%20los%20criterios%20anteriores)) ([educacion.rionegro.gov.ar](https://educacion.rionegro.gov.ar/nota/3925#:~:text=Derechos%20Humanos%3A%20www,De%20acuerdo%20a%20lo)). This coordinated process guarantees every applicant a place in a public secondary school ([rionegro.gov.ar](https://rionegro.gov.ar/articulo/51283/siguen-las-inscripciones-de-estudiantes-para-sala-de-4-1-grado-y-1-ano#:~:text=Con%20este%20procedimiento%20de%20asignaci%C3%B3n,todos%20las%20y%20los%20estudiantes)). The unified assignment system was first implemented in the mid-2010s (formalized by Resolution 4080/2014) ([registrocivil.rionegro.gov.ar](https://registrocivil.rionegro.gov.ar/articulo/13500/el-lunes-comienza-la-inscripcion-de-estudiantes-para-el-periodo-escolar-2016#:~:text=De%20acuerdo%20a%20lo%20que,prioridad%20de%20los%20siguientes%20criterios)) and was significantly reformed in 2016 with new guidelines under the Escuela Secundaria de Río Negro (ESRN) model ([www.educacion.rionegro.gov.ar](https://www.educacion.rionegro.gov.ar/nota/4802#:~:text=A%20trav%C3%A9s%20de%20esta%20nueva,resoluci%C3%B3n%20se%20aprueba%20una%20nueva)). Private secondary schools in Bariloche do not participate in this centralized assignment system, handling admissions independently.

There is no coordinated tertiary admission system in San Carlos de Bariloche. Instead, each higher education institution administers its own admissions, consistent with Argentina’s policy of university autonomy ([www.infoleg.gob.ar](https://www.infoleg.gob.ar/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/LEY-AED-2019.html#:~:text=Art%C3%ADculo%2035.,admisi%C3%B3n%20que%20cada%20instituci%C3%B3n%20establezca)). A local university official emphasized that each institution can define its own policies because universities are autonomous ([www.anbariloche.com.ar](https://www.anbariloche.com.ar/noticias/2024/12/04/96366-arancelamiento-universitario-que-posicion-toman-las-instituciones-de-bariloche#:~:text=La%20medida%2C%20que%20si%20bien,que%20las%20universidades%20son%20aut%C3%B3nomas)). Applicants in Bariloche do not submit ranked preferences through a central platform; they must apply directly to individual universities or institutes. Admission to local public institutions (such as the National University of Río Negro and the University of Comahue’s Bariloche campus) is generally open to all who meet basic requirements (e.g. secondary school completion), reflecting the national principle of unrestricted access to higher education ([www.scielo.org.mx](https://www.scielo.org.mx/scielo.php?lng=es&nrm=iso&pid=S0185-27602023000300104&script=sci_arttext#:~:text=Analizar%20el%20acceso%20en%20la,42)). For programs with limited seats (for example, medicine), any selection criteria (such as academic performance or entrance exams) are set by the institution rather than by a centralized authority. No citywide algorithm or single-offer matching process exists for tertiary education in Bariloche; thus no CCAS has been adopted, and consequently no reforms of such a system have occurred.

San Salvador de Jujuy does not have a fully coordinated school choice system for primary education. Enrollment into public primary schools is handled at the school level under provincial guidelines rather than through a centralized algorithm. Parents typically register their children at a local school, with priority given to certain criteria like siblings of current students and residence in the school’s catchment area ([www.quepasajujuy.com.ar](https://www.quepasajujuy.com.ar/jujuy/inscripciones-para-los-jardines-de-infantes-en-jujuy/#:~:text=El%20Ministerio%20de%20Educaci%C3%B3n%20de,ya%20pertenecen%20a%20cada%20jard%C3%ADn)) ([www.quepasajujuy.com.ar](https://www.quepasajujuy.com.ar/jujuy/inscripciones-para-los-jardines-de-infantes-en-jujuy/#:~:text=,ni%C3%B1os%20dentro%20del%20radio%20escolar)). If applications exceed available spots at a given school, a lottery may be used to allocate the seats (as seen in provincial preschool admissions) ([www.quepasajujuy.com.ar](https://www.quepasajujuy.com.ar/jujuy/inscripciones-para-los-jardines-de-infantes-en-jujuy/#:~:text=En%20el%20caso%20de%20la,los%20hermanos%20de%20alumnos%20actuales)). Families do not submit ranked preferences for multiple primary schools, and each school manages its own intake. Therefore, no single-offer centralized assignment mechanism exists for primary education in the city, meaning the system is uncoordinated.

San Salvador de Jujuy (following provincial policy) uses a centralized admission system for public secondary schools. Families register students online and select a preferred school; if the chosen school is not oversubscribed, the student simply confirms enrollment. If it is oversubscribed, a centralized process allocates seats. For most schools this is done by a computerized lottery (using a random "momento" timestamp draw), with special priority given to certain groups such as students with disabilities, top academic achievers (flag bearers), and those with siblings at the school ([educacion.jujuy.gob.ar](https://educacion.jujuy.gob.ar/ingreso2026/#:~:text=,la%20misma%20oportunidad%20de%20ingresar)) ([educacion.jujuy.gob.ar](https://educacion.jujuy.gob.ar/ingreso-preguntas/#:~:text=ESTUDIANTES%20CON%20DISCAPACIDAD%20aquellos%20estudiantes,la%20instituci%C3%B3n%20de%20Educaci%C3%B3n%20Primaria)). In a subset of highly demanded schools (about 15–20 institutions), an entrance exam in core subjects is required; admission to those is based on the evaluative test results ([educacion.jujuy.gob.ar](https://educacion.jujuy.gob.ar/ingreso2026/#:~:text=,De%20esta%20manera%20todos)). Each student receives at most one offer per round of assignment, and unplaced students can apply again in a second round. This Coordinated Choice and Assignment System was first implemented in 2021 via an online pre‐inscription and lottery process ([educacion.jujuy.gob.ar](https://educacion.jujuy.gob.ar/2021/09/30/la-preinscripcion-virtual-a-1o-ano-de-secundaria-inicia-el-18-de-octubre/#:~:text=Asimismo%2C%20precis%C3%B3%20que%20%E2%80%9Cestas%20im%C3%A1genes,necesarios%20para%20confirmar%20la%20vacante%E2%80%9D)), and was updated in 2024 to introduce the exam requirement for certain schools ([boletinoficial.jujuy.gob.ar](https://boletinoficial.jujuy.gob.ar/?p=297880#:~:text=ARTICULO%202%C2%B0.,II%20de%20la%20presente%20Resoluci%C3%B3n)). Private secondary schools in the city are not part of this centralized system.

In San Salvador de Jujuy, tertiary education admissions are not handled by a single centralized system. Applicants apply separately to multiple institutions or programs, rather than submitting one ranked preference list ([educacion.jujuy.gob.ar](https://educacion.jujuy.gob.ar/2025/11/26/inician-las-preinscripciones-para-el-ingreso-a-carreras-de-educacion-superior-2026/#:~:text=Desde%20el%2015%20de%20diciembre,que%20una%20persona%20puede%20inscribirse)). Public tertiary institutes (Institutos de Educación Superior, IES) run by the provincial government use a common online platform (NEXO) for applications ([prensa.jujuy.gob.ar](https://prensa.jujuy.gob.ar/sistema-nexo/comienza-preinscripcion-carreras-nivel-superior-n117818#:~:text=Por%20primera%20vez%2C%20a%20trav%C3%A9s,el%20acceso%20a%20la%20informaci%C3%B3n)), but each institute admits students independently. Admission is based on each institution’s entrance course and mandatory exam; candidates are ranked by exam performance (academic merit) and admitted up to the available slots ([educacion.jujuy.gob.ar](https://educacion.jujuy.gob.ar/2025/11/26/inician-las-preinscripciones-para-el-ingreso-a-carreras-de-educacion-superior-2026/#:~:text=El%20cursillo%20contar%C3%A1%20con%20una,cupos%20disponibles%20en%20cada%20IES)). For example, the National University of Jujuy conducts its own preparatory modules and entrance exam, producing a merit list to select a limited number of new students (e.g., 600 seats) ([noticias.unju.edu.ar](https://noticias.unju.edu.ar/noticia.php?id=4645#:~:text=Quienes%20aprueben%20los%20m%C3%B3dulos%20podr%C3%A1n,ser%C3%A1n%20los%20600%20nuevos%20ingresantes)). Because students can receive offers from more than one institution and must choose where to enroll, no centralized algorithm assigns a single offer per applicant. No evidence of a fully Coordinated Choice and Assignment System (CCAS) was found; the 2024 introduction of the NEXO portal streamlined the process but did not implement a centralized matching mechanism ([prensa.jujuy.gob.ar](https://prensa.jujuy.gob.ar/sistema-nexo/comienza-preinscripcion-carreras-nivel-superior-n117818#:~:text=Por%20primera%20vez%2C%20a%20trav%C3%A9s,el%20acceso%20a%20la%20informaci%C3%B3n)).

Yerevan’s primary school admissions are managed through a centralized online registration system introduced in 2019 ([www.armedu.am](https://www.armedu.am/index.php/am/news/view/2820#:~:text=%D4%B5%D6%80%D6%87%D5%A1%D5%B6%D5%AB%20%D5%BA%D5%A5%D5%BF%D5%A1%D5%AF%D5%A1%D5%B6%20%D5%B0%D5%A1%D5%B6%D6%80%D5%A1%D5%AF%D6%80%D5%A9%D5%A1%D5%AF%D5%A1%D5%B6%20%D5%A4%D5%BA%D6%80%D5%B8%D6%81%D5%B6%D5%A5%D6%80%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%B4%202019,%D5%A7%20%D5%A2%D5%A1%D6%81%D5%A1%D5%BC%D5%A1%D5%BA%D5%A5%D5%BD%20%D5%A7%D5%AC%D5%A5%D5%AF%D5%BF%D6%80%D5%B8%D5%B6%D5%A1%D5%B5%D5%AB%D5%B6%20%D5%A3%D6%80%D5%A1%D5%B6%D6%81%D5%B4%D5%A1%D5%B6%20%D5%A5%D5%B2%D5%A1%D5%B6%D5%A1%D5%AF%D5%B8%D5%BE)). All public first-grade seats in the city are allocated via the national platform (hayt.emis.am) run by the Ministry of Education ([english.hartak.am](https://english.hartak.am/services/2eebb462-a9f2-4cb8-92fe-617be85adde4/online/#:~:text=Admission%20of%20first,to%20view%20the%20English%20version)), while private schools handle admissions independently. Parents do not submit ranked preferences; they register their child at one chosen school on the platform, provided that school has available seats ([english.hartak.am](https://english.hartak.am/services/2eebb462-a9f2-4cb8-92fe-617be85adde4/online/#:~:text=,your%20region%20and%20administrative%20district)). Admission is essentially first-come-first-served within designated phases ([www.panarmenian.net](https://www.panarmenian.net/eng/news/323203/#:~:text=starts%20on%20June%209%2C%20the,22%2C%20the%20first%20phase%20is)): an early phase for priority groups (e.g. siblings at the school, children of school staff or relocated civil servants, and vulnerable or disabled children living near the school) ([english.hartak.am](https://english.hartak.am/services/2eebb462-a9f2-4cb8-92fe-617be85adde4/online/#:~:text=,parent%20working%20at%20the%20school)), followed by a general phase for all other applicants. Schools are not permitted to administer any entrance exams or academic screening ([english.hartak.am](https://english.hartak.am/services/2eebb462-a9f2-4cb8-92fe-617be85adde4/online/#:~:text=,part%20of%20the%20admission%20process)), and children with special educational needs are admitted on an equal basis. In cases of twins or other multiple siblings, registering one child guarantees admission for the others in the same school, even if capacity is exceeded ([www.panarmenian.net](https://www.panarmenian.net/eng/news/323203/#:~:text=for%20parents%20choosing%20that%20option,Enrollment%20will)). The system first piloted in Yerevan has since been expanded nationwide ([arminfo.info](https://arminfo.info/full_news.php?id=92140&lang=3#:~:text=ArmInfo.%C2%A0%C2%A0The%20registration%C2%A0process%20for%20first,will%20begin%20on%20June%209)), and there have been no major changes to its core structure since the 2019 launch.

Secondary school admissions in Yerevan lack a centralized matching system. Enrollment in public schools (e.g., for first grade) is managed via an online registration portal implemented in 2019 ([newsarmenia.am](https://newsarmenia.am/news/armenia/v-erevane-vvoditsya-sistema-onlayn-zapisi-pervoklassnikov-v-shkoly/#:~:text=%D0%A1%2015%20%D0%BC%D0%B0%D1%8F%202019%20%D0%B3%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%B0,%D1%81%D1%82%D0%BE%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%86%D1%8B%20%D1%82%D0%BE%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%BA%D0%BE%20%D1%87%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B7%20%D1%81%D0%BF%D0%B5%D1%86%D0%B8%D0%B0%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%BD%D1%8B%D0%B9%20%D1%81%D0%B0%D0%B9%D1%82)). Parents choose a school and register on a first-come, first-served basis ([escs.am](https://escs.am/ru/faq#:~:text=%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%B8%D0%B2%D0%B8%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%B3%D0%B8%D0%B5%D0%B9%20%D0%B4%D0%BB%D1%8F%20%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B3%D0%B8%D1%81%D1%82%D1%80%D0%B0%D1%86%D0%B8%D0%B8%20%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B1%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%BA%D0%B0,%D0%BC%D0%B5%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B0%20%D0%B2%20%D1%88%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%BB%D0%B5%20%D0%B1%D1%83%D0%B4%D1%83%D1%82%20%D0%B8%D1%81%D1%87%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%BF%D0%B0%D0%BD%D1%8B)), without listing multiple preferences or receiving algorithm-generated assignments. No specific priority criteria (like catchment or sibling preference) are applied by design ([escs.am](https://escs.am/ru/faq#:~:text=%D0%A1%D0%BE%D0%B3%D0%BB%D0%B0%D1%81%D0%BD%D0%BE%20%D0%BF%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B2%D0%BE%D0%BC%D1%83%20%D0%B0%D0%B1%D0%B7%D0%B0%D1%86%D1%83%20%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B0%D1%82%D1%8C%D0%B8%2028%2C,%D0%BC%D0%B5%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B0%20%D0%B2%20%D1%88%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%BB%D0%B5%20%D0%B1%D1%83%D0%B4%D1%83%D1%82%20%D0%B8%D1%81%D1%87%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%BF%D0%B0%D0%BD%D1%8B)); all applicants have equal access until school capacity is reached. Private and specialized secondary schools run their own independent admission exams and processes, separate from the city-run system. Therefore, Yerevan does not operate a coordinated choice and assignment system for secondary education.

Tertiary admissions in Yerevan (and Armenia nationally) are not managed by a single coordinated matching system. Instead, a centralized **Unified State Entrance Examination** is used, but application and placement are handled in stages. Each applicant initially applies to only one university and program in the first wave; admissions are decided by exam rankings for that choice ([vuzopedia.ru](https://vuzopedia.ru/articles/4730#:~:text=%D0%9F%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%82%D1%83%D0%BF%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B5%20%D0%B2%20%D0%B2%D1%83%D0%B7%20%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%83%D1%89%D0%B5%D1%81%D1%82%D0%B2%D0%BB%D1%8F%D0%B5%D1%82%D1%81%D1%8F%20%D0%B2,%D0%B2%20%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%BC%20%D0%B8%D0%BB%D0%B8%20%D0%BD%D0%B5%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%BA%D0%B8%D1%85%20%D0%B2%D1%83%D0%B7%D0%B0%D1%85)). After this main round, any remaining vacant seats are filled in a second wave where unplaced applicants can apply to up to six additional programs ([www.e-draft.am](https://www.e-draft.am/projects/3054/justification#:~:text=%D5%A4%D5%AB%D5%B4%D5%B8%D6%80%D5%A4%D5%B6%D5%A5%D6%80%D5%A8%20%D5%B0%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%AC%D5%AB%D5%BD%D5%AB%2019,%D5%A1%D5%BC%D5%AF%D5%A1%20%D5%A5%D5%B6%20%D5%A9%D5%A1%D6%83%D5%B8%D6%82%D6%80%20%D5%BF%D5%A5%D5%B2%D5%A5%D6%80)). This process often results in some students receiving multiple admission offers (especially in the second wave) and then choosing one, rather than a single algorithmically assigned offer ([arminfo.info](https://arminfo.info/full_news.php?id=49564&lang=3#:~:text=,required%2C%20regardless%20of%20the%20profession)). All public and private universities in Yerevan participate under the national framework ([nuaca.am](https://nuaca.am/archives/ads/on-the-results-of-the-appeals-for-intra-university-entrance-exams-for-full-time-studies-of-the-2025-2026-academic-year/?lang=en#:~:text=Guided%20by%20Clause%2059%20of,and%20%E2%80%9CDesign%2C%E2%80%9D%20have%20remained%20unchanged)). **Academic criteria** dominate admissions – primarily the unified exam scores (and in some cases high school performance) determine placement ([www.sglmc.am](https://www.sglmc.am/hy/college/department/admission-on-a-general-basis#:~:text=1,%D5%A8%D5%B6%D5%A4%D5%B0%D5%A1%D5%B6%D5%B8%D6%82%D6%80%20%D5%A1%D5%BC%D5%A1%D5%BE%D5%A5%D5%AC%D5%A1%D5%A3%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%B5%D5%B6%20%D5%A3%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%B4%D5%A1%D6%80%20%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%B6%D5%A5%D6%81%D5%B8%D5%B2%20%D5%A4%D5%AB%D5%B4%D5%B8%D6%80%D5%A4%D5%A8)). Certain tie-breaker advantages or reserved quotas exist for specific groups, such as national minority students (who have dedicated state-funded slots) ([escs.am](https://escs.am/am/news/30475#:~:text=%D5%86%D5%A1%D5%AD%D5%A1%D6%80%D5%A1%D6%80%20%D4%BA%D5%A1%D5%B6%D5%B6%D5%A1%20%D4%B1%D5%B6%D5%A4%D6%80%D5%A5%D5%A1%D5%BD%D5%B5%D5%A1%D5%B6%D5%A8%2C%20%D5%AE%D5%A1%D5%B6%D5%B8%D5%A9%D5%A1%D5%B6%D5%A1%D5%AC%D5%B8%D5%BE%20%D5%A8%D5%B6%D5%A4%D5%B0%D5%A1%D5%B6%D5%B8%D6%82%D6%80,%D5%A9%D5%A1%D6%83%D5%B8%D6%82%D6%80%20%D5%BF%D5%A5%D5%B2%D5%A5%D6%80%D5%AB%20%D5%B4%D6%80%D6%81%D5%B8%D6%82%D5%B5%D5%A9%D5%AB%20%D5%AF%D5%A1%D5%A6%D5%B4%D5%A1%D5%AF%D5%A5%D6%80%D5%BA%D5%B4%D5%A1%D5%B6%20%D5%B0%D5%A1%D6%80%D6%81%D5%A8)) and academic Olympiad winners ([www.sglmc.am](https://www.sglmc.am/hy/college/department/admission-on-a-general-basis#:~:text=%D5%A5,%D5%A1%D5%BC%D5%A1%D5%BB%D5%AB%D5%B6%20%D5%AF%D5%A1%D6%80%D5%A3%D5%AB%20%D5%A4%D5%AB%D5%BA%D5%AC%D5%B8%D5%B4%20%D5%BD%D5%BF%D5%A1%D6%81%D5%A1%D5%AE%20%D5%A4%D5%AB%D5%B4%D5%B8%D6%80%D5%A4%D5%AB%D5%B6)). Armenia introduced the unified exam system in **2012** by government decision ([nuaca.am](https://nuaca.am/archives/ads/on-the-results-of-the-appeals-for-intra-university-entrance-exams-for-full-time-studies-of-the-2025-2026-academic-year/?lang=en#:~:text=Guided%20by%20Clause%2059%20of,and%20%E2%80%9CDesign%2C%E2%80%9D%20have%20remained%20unchanged)), and a notable reform in **2021** refined the application procedure (e.g. introducing the current two-wave process) ([www.arlis.am](https://www.arlis.am/hy/acts/151376#:~:text=1%20%D5%A1%D5%BA%D6%80%D5%AB%D5%AC%D5%AB%202021%20%D5%A9%D5%BE%D5%A1%D5%AF%D5%A1%D5%B6%D5%AB%20N,%D5%86)).

Primary school admissions in Adelaide (South Australia) are handled through local school enrollment policies rather than any centralized city-wide matching system. These policies apply to government (public) schools only, since non-government schools manage their own admissions processes independently ([www.education.sa.gov.au](https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/enrol-school-or-preschool/school-enrolment/starting-school#:~:text=Learn%20how%20to%20apply%20to,government%20schools%20on%20this%20page)). Public primary schools typically serve defined local catchment areas (school zones) and prioritize children residing in their zone for enrollment ([www.education.sa.gov.au](https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/enrol-school-or-preschool/school-enrolment/placement-school#:~:text=A%20school%20zone%20is%20a,who%20live%20inside%20that%20zone)). Families wishing to enroll a child in a non-local primary school must apply directly to that school, and they may submit applications to multiple schools concurrently ([www.education.sa.gov.au](https://www.education.sa.gov.au/primary-school-enrolment#:~:text=You%20can%20apply%20to%20enrol,local%20school%20is%20not%20successful)). Offers for out-of-zone applicants are subject to space availability; if a school has more applicants than places, the Department for Education policy guides the school to consider criteria like the distance from the child's home, whether a sibling is already attending, specific curriculum needs, and other special circumstances (e.g. Aboriginal or special needs status) in deciding admissions ([www.education.sa.gov.au](https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/enrol-school-or-preschool/school-enrolment/placement-school#:~:text=When%20demand%20from%20non,places%2C%20the%20school%20will%20consider)) ([www.education.sa.gov.au](https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/enrol-school-or-preschool/school-enrolment/placement-school#:~:text=,a%20custody%20or%20guardianship%20order)). There is no centralized algorithm or single-offer coordination for primary admissions—each school extends offers independently (though under common policy guidelines) ([www.education.sa.gov.au](https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/enrol-school-or-preschool/school-enrolment/starting-school#:~:text=You%20can%20get%20a%20registration,primary%20school%20you%27re%20interested%20in)). Unlike secondary school placement in Adelaide (which uses a coordinated statewide preference system), primary school admissions have no unified choice system ([www.education.sa.gov.au](https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/enrol-school-or-preschool/school-enrolment/starting-school#:~:text=)). Consequently, no formal coordinated choice/assignment system has been adopted or reformed in Adelaide’s primary education sector.

In Adelaide (South Australia), admission to public secondary schools is managed through a centralised process. Families register their preferences for government high schools via a statewide transition system operated by the Department for Education ([www.education.sa.gov.au](https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/enrol-school-or-preschool/school-enrolment/starting-secondary-school#:~:text=Every%20effort%20is%20made%20to,from%20your%20registration%20of%20interest)) ([adelaidehs.sa.edu.au](https://adelaidehs.sa.edu.au/enrolment/year-7-enrolment#:~:text=The%20Department%20for%20Education%20runs,au)). Each student is guaranteed a place at their local zoned school, but can apply for other schools; a single offer of enrolment is made based on the highest possible preference available ([www.education.sa.gov.au](https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/enrol-school-or-preschool/school-enrolment/starting-secondary-school#:~:text=Every%20effort%20is%20made%20to,from%20your%20registration%20of%20interest)). Local students have first priority (catchment zoning) ([www.education.sa.gov.au](https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/enrol-school-or-preschool/school-enrolment/placement-school#:~:text=A%20school%20zone%20is%20a,who%20live%20inside%20that%20zone)), and if a school has space for out-of-zone applicants, selection is determined by criteria such as sibling attendance, distance from home, curriculum or special program needs, family or social links, and transport considerations ([www.education.sa.gov.au](https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/enrol-school-or-preschool/school-enrolment/placement-school#:~:text=Some%C2%A0schools%20have%20a%20shared%20zone,nominate%20a%20preferred%20local%20school)). Certain selective or special interest programs (e.g. gifted/talented, sports, language) allow students to enroll regardless of zone if they meet specific entrance requirements ([www.education.sa.gov.au](https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/enrol-school-or-preschool/school-enrolment/placement-school#:~:text=,a%20custody%20or%20guardianship%20order)). This coordinated choice and assignment system applies to public schools only, while private and faith-based schools manage admissions independently. A notable policy change in 2020 removed automatic entry for younger siblings of students admitted via selective programs, tightening that priority rule ([www.education.sa.gov.au](https://www.education.sa.gov.au/parents-and-families/enrol-school-or-preschool/school-enrolment/placement-school#:~:text=Siblings%20already%20in%20a%20selective,interest%20program%20in%20high%20school)). In 2022, the system was expanded to include Year 7 as the entry point to high school, aligning South Australia’s secondary schooling with other states.

In Adelaide, tertiary admissions are coordinated through the South Australian Tertiary Admissions Centre (SATAC) ([satac.edu.au](https://satac.edu.au/satacs-role#:~:text=Established%20in%201977%20by%20the,education%20institutions%20in%20the%20state)), which serves as a single application and offer hub for multiple institutions. Applicants submit a ranked list of up to six course preferences ([www.satac.edu.au](https://www.satac.edu.au/preferences#:~:text=The%20courses%20you%20add%20to,SATAC%20application%20are%20your%20preferences)) and receive at most one offer – their highest-ranked eligible choice ([www.satac.edu.au](https://www.satac.edu.au/preferences#:~:text=Preferences%20and%20offers)). SATAC processes applications and provides lists of eligible applicants to institutions, which then determine offers that SATAC issues on their behalf ([satac.edu.au](https://satac.edu.au/satacs-role#:~:text=SATAC%E2%80%99s%20job%20is%20to%20process,the%20offers%20on%20their%20behalf)). The system includes both public and private tertiary institutions ([satac.edu.au](https://satac.edu.au/satacs-role#:~:text=,Torrens%20University%20Australia)). Admission is primarily merit-based (using the ATAR or equivalent academic score) ([www.adelaide.edu.au](https://www.adelaide.edu.au/news/print60381.html#:~:text=The%20SATAC%20Board%20also%20agreed,for%20the%202014%20university%20intakes)). However, adjustment factors are applied for equity and subject-based criteria: under the Universities Equity Scheme, students from disadvantaged socioeconomic backgrounds (e.g., low SES or rural) can receive bonus points, and under the Language, Literacy and Mathematics Scheme, students are rewarded for certain high school subjects ([www.adelaide.edu.au](https://www.adelaide.edu.au/news/print60381.html#:~:text=agreed%20unanimously%20at%20their%20meeting,off%20scores%2C%20and)) ([www.satac.edu.au](https://www.satac.edu.au/adjustment-factors#:~:text=SATAC%E2%80%99s%20participating%20institutions%20have%20two,provide%20adjustment%20factors%20to%20applicants)). These adjustments (capped at 9 points total) influence an applicant’s selection rank ([www.satac.edu.au](https://www.satac.edu.au/adjustment-factors#:~:text=We%20will%20adjust%20your%20aggregate,a%20maximum%20of%209%20points)) but do not depend on preference order ([www.satac.edu.au](https://www.satac.edu.au/preferences#:~:text=Your%20selection%20rank%20is%20not,the%20order%20of%20your%20preferences)). The matching mechanism effectively ensures applicants are admitted to the highest preference for which they qualify, reflecting a deferred acceptance approach ([www.satac.edu.au](https://www.satac.edu.au/preferences#:~:text=Preferences%20and%20offers)). The centralized system was introduced in 1977 ([satac.edu.au](https://satac.edu.au/satacs-role#:~:text=Established%20in%201977%20by%20the,education%20institutions%20in%20the%20state)). A major reform in 2016 standardized bonus point policies across institutions to improve fairness and transparency ([www.adelaide.edu.au](https://www.adelaide.edu.au/news/print60381.html#:~:text=The%20SATAC%20Board%20also%20agreed,to%20be%20implemented%20in%202016)).

Primary school admissions in Brisbane are managed through local catchment areas and not via a centralized choice system ([brisbanekids.com.au](https://brisbanekids.com.au/school-catchments-in-brisbane/#:~:text=This%20does%20not%20mean%20that,placed%20on%20a%20waiting%20list)). Each state (public) primary school guarantees enrollment for children living in its catchment zone, ensuring every student can attend a local school ([brisbanekids.com.au](https://brisbanekids.com.au/school-catchments-in-brisbane/#:~:text=As%20defined%20by%20the%20Queensland,%E2%80%9D)). Families may apply to schools outside their catchment, but these out-of-catchment enrollments are only accepted if capacity allows and are placed on waiting lists processed in the order received ([www.qld.gov.au](https://www.qld.gov.au/education/schools/find/enrolment/catchment#:~:text=area%2C%20but%20enrolment%20is%20not,placed%20on%20a%20waiting%20list)). There is no citywide algorithm assigning students to schools; offers are handled by individual schools under Department of Education guidelines rather than a single coordinated process ([www.qld.gov.au](https://www.qld.gov.au/education/schools/find/enrolment/catchment#:~:text=area%2C%20but%20enrolment%20is%20not,placed%20on%20a%20waiting%20list)) ([www.readkong.com](https://www.readkong.com/page/enrolment-in-state-primary-secondary-and-special-schools-7692803#:~:text=apply%20to%20enrol%20in%20any,they%20live%20within%20the%20local)). Admission priorities are based on residence (zone) and other criteria defined by each school's enrolment management plan—for example, siblings of current students and certain special needs or programs can be considered as if local in some cases ([ppr.qed.qld.gov.au](https://ppr.qed.qld.gov.au/pp/school-enrolment-management-plans-school-emps-procedure#:~:text=,QGSO)). Private schools have their own independent admission procedures and are not part of any coordinated scheme ([brisbanekids.com.au](https://brisbanekids.com.au/school-catchments-in-brisbane/#:~:text=,Open%20Days%20at%20Brisbane%20Schools)). Brisbane has not adopted a Coordinated Choice and Assignment System, so there is no specific adoption or reform year; the catchment-based approach has been longstanding with periodic policy updates (e.g., updated guidelines in 2024 ([ppr.qed.qld.gov.au](https://ppr.qed.qld.gov.au/pp/enrolment-in-state-primary-secondary-and-special-schools-procedure#:~:text=Version%20number%207.12%20,effective%2019%20March%202024))) rather than a single reform.

Brisbane, like the rest of Queensland, does not use a centralized school choice system for secondary admissions ([education.qld.gov.au](https://education.qld.gov.au/parents-and-carers/enrolment/choosing-a-school#:~:text=Children%20usually%20attend%20the%20state,they%20meet%20specific%20enrolment%20criteria)). Students are guaranteed a place at their local state high school based on designated catchment zones ([www.qld.gov.au](https://www.qld.gov.au/education/schools/find/enrolment/catchment#:~:text=Catchment%20areas%20ensure%20every%20Queensland,at%20their%20local%20state%20school)). Families may apply to public high schools outside their catchment if the desired school has available places ([education.qld.gov.au](https://education.qld.gov.au/parents-and-carers/enrolment/choosing-a-school#:~:text=Children%20usually%20attend%20the%20state,they%20meet%20specific%20enrolment%20criteria)); however, parents must contact each such school directly to seek out-of-catchment enrolment ([www.brisbanetimes.com.au](https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/seq-s-most-crowded-schools-and-how-many-kids-live-out-of-their-catchment-20230608-p5dexr.html#:~:text=%E2%80%9CParents%20have%20the%20choice%20of,enrolling%20at%20a%20school%20that)). Oversubscribed schools implement Enrolment Management Plans to prioritize local in-zone students and may limit out-of-catchment admissions to specific categories (e.g., siblings of current students, children of school staff, or special program entrants) ([www.brisbanetimes.com.au](https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/seq-s-most-crowded-schools-and-how-many-kids-live-out-of-their-catchment-20230608-p5dexr.html#:~:text=The%20spokesman%20said%20some%20schools,and%20siblings%20of%20current%20students)). Private and independent secondary schools manage their own admissions separately, with no involvement in any central allocation ([www.bne.catholic.edu.au](https://www.bne.catholic.edu.au/students-parents/FrequentlyAskedQuestions#:~:text=Each%20Brisbane%20Catholic%20Education%20,%E2%80%8B)). Because there is no city-wide Coordinated Choice and Assignment System (CCAS), attributes like preference list length, centralized priority criteria, assignment mechanism, or adoption year are not applicable.

Brisbane, in the state of Queensland, uses a state-wide centralized tertiary admission system operated by the Queensland Tertiary Admissions Centre (QTAC) ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queensland_Tertiary_Admissions_Centre#:~:text=The%20Queensland%20Tertiary%20Admissions%20Centre,entirely%20by%20student%20application%20fees)). Under QTAC, applicants submit a single application listing up to six preferences for courses across different institutions ([abcdocz.com](https://abcdocz.com/doc/387142/#:~:text=Choosing%20your%20preferences%20%28cont,satisfy%20the%20Minimum%20Entry%20Requirements)). Admissions are decided through a centralized algorithm that ensures each applicant gets at most one offer to their highest eligible preference ([abcdocz.com](https://abcdocz.com/doc/387142/#:~:text=%EF%82%A7%20It%20is%20essential%20that,for%20your%20highest%20eligible%20preference)). Selection is primarily based on academic merit (ATAR or adjusted selection rank) ([www.qtac.edu.au](https://www.qtac.edu.au/t2admissions-criteria/#:~:text=QTAC%20places%20all%20competing%20applicants,highest%20ATAR%2Fselection%20rank%20second%20etc)). However, equity adjustments (such as for socio-economic disadvantage under an Educational Access Scheme or for a rural background through reserved place quotas) can increase an applicant's selection rank for certain courses ([www.qtac.edu.au](https://www.qtac.edu.au/t2admissions-criteria/#:~:text=Educational%20Access%20Scheme%20)) ([www.qtac.edu.au](https://www.qtac.edu.au/t2admissions-criteria/#:~:text=Rural%20Access%20Scheme)). The matching process follows an 'immediate acceptance' mechanism: the system checks each applicant's preferences in order and grants an offer to the first preference for which they meet the cutoff, if any ([pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9802117/#:~:text=The%20UAC%27s%20offer%20algorithm%20is,follows%20for%20a%20given%20applicant)). QTAC has coordinated admissions since 1975 ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queensland_Tertiary_Admissions_Centre#:~:text=Formation%3A%201975%20Type%3A%20Non,tertiary%20education%20admissions%20application%20processing)), and a major reform in 2020 introduced the national ATAR scoring system and aligned Queensland’s admission process with other Australian states ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queensland_Tertiary_Admissions_Centre#:~:text=Starting%20for%20the%202020%20cohort%2C,school%20and%20university%20entry%20systems)). Most public and private universities in Brisbane participate in QTAC’s coordinated system, though a few private institutions may handle some admissions (for example, certain programs at Bond University) outside this central process ([abcdocz.com](https://abcdocz.com/doc/387142/#:~:text=%EF%82%A7%20Australian%20Catholic%20University%20%EF%82%A7,%EF%82%A7%20The%20University%20of%20Queensland)).

Canberra’s primary school admissions are managed through a centralized system for public schools. Every child is guaranteed a place at their local public school (determined by Priority Enrolment Area zoning) ([www.act.gov.au](https://www.act.gov.au/education-and-training/find-a-school-and-enrol/find-a-school-in-your-priority-enrolment-area#:~:text=From%20kindergarten%20to%20year%2012%2C,public%20school%20within%20their%20PEA)). Families may apply for one out-of-area public school, but out-of-area placements are not guaranteed and depend on available capacity ([www.act.gov.au](https://www.act.gov.au/education-and-training/find-a-school-and-enrol/apply-to-a-school-outside-your-area#:~:text=place,a%20school%20within%20your%20PEA)). If an out-of-area application is unsuccessful, the student receives an offer at their local (in-area) school ([www.act.gov.au](https://www.act.gov.au/education-and-training/find-a-school-and-enrol/apply-to-a-school-outside-your-area#:~:text=place,a%20school%20within%20your%20PEA)). Out-of-area admissions are considered according to official priority criteria: for example, a court order or special wellbeing needs that require a specific school, and whether the child has a sibling at the requested school ([www.act.gov.au](https://www.act.gov.au/education-and-training/find-a-school-and-enrol/apply-to-a-school-outside-your-area#:~:text=1,suitable%20school%20where%20enrolling%20the)) ([www.act.gov.au](https://www.act.gov.au/education-and-training/find-a-school-and-enrol/apply-to-a-school-outside-your-area#:~:text=3,Torres%20Strait%20Islander%20kinship%20relationships)). In cases of oversubscription (such as at certain early childhood schools), distance from the school can be used to rank applicants ([www.act.gov.au](https://www.act.gov.au/education-and-training/find-a-school-and-enrol/apply-to-a-school-outside-your-area#:~:text=Where%20there%20are%20not%20enough,child%20lives%20to%20the%20school)). The assignment process is coordinated by the ACT Education Directorate via an online application portal, ensuring each student gets a single offer. School principals, following the Directorate’s guidelines, make the final decisions on out-of-area enrolments based on the stated criteria rather than a lottery or algorithmic match ([www.act.gov.au](https://www.act.gov.au/education-and-training/find-a-school-and-enrol/apply-to-a-school-outside-your-area#:~:text=The%20principal%20will%20make%20a,as%20part%20of%20your%20application)). Only government (public) schools are part of this coordinated system – non-government (private and Catholic) schools in Canberra conduct their own admissions processes ([www.act.gov.au](https://www.act.gov.au/our-canberra/enrol-in-school#:~:text=Find%20public%20and%20non,Enrol%20in%20a%20public%20school)).

Secondary school admissions in Canberra (ACT) are managed through a centralized process by the ACT Education Directorate. All local students are guaranteed a place at their designated Priority Enrolment Area (PEA) public school (i.e., neighborhood school) ([www.cmtedd.act.gov.au](https://www.cmtedd.act.gov.au/open_government/inform/act_government_media_releases/yvette-berry-mla-media-releases/2025/act-public-school-enrolments-now-open-for-2026#:~:text=Every%20ACT%20child%20from%20kindergarten,within%20their%20priority%20enrolment%20area)). Families apply via a single online form for public schools; they may nominate **one** out-of-area school if desired ([www.act.gov.au](https://www.act.gov.au/education-and-training/find-a-school-and-enrol/apply-to-a-school-outside-your-area#:~:text=You%20can%20apply%20to%20enrol,out%20of%20area%20enrolment%20application)). Each student receives a single offer – either their local school or the one alternate choice if it can be accommodated ([www.act.gov.au](https://www.act.gov.au/education-and-training/find-a-school-and-enrol/enrol-in-a-public-school?utm%5C_medium=redirect&utm%5C_source=education#:~:text=If%20you%20applied%20to%20a,to%20accept%20an%20enrolment%20offer)). Out-of-area applications are limited and assessed under strict criteria: for example, an existing sibling at the school, special curriculum not offered at the local school (such as a language program), or exceptional student wellbeing needs ([www.act.gov.au](https://www.act.gov.au/education-and-training/find-a-school-and-enrol/apply-to-a-school-outside-your-area#:~:text=4,has%20a%20sibling%C2%A0who%20will%20be)). Oversubscribed schools are categorized as **Category A** (high-demand schools that typically cannot take any out-of-area students) ([www.act.gov.au](https://www.act.gov.au/education-and-training/find-a-school-and-enrol/apply-to-a-school-outside-your-area#:~:text=Category%20A%20schools%20are%20in,who%20live%20outside%20their%20PEA)), while **Category B** schools may accept some out-of-area enrollments if space is available ([www.act.gov.au](https://www.act.gov.au/education-and-training/find-a-school-and-enrol/apply-to-a-school-outside-your-area#:~:text=Category%20B%20schools%20usually%20have,for%20students%20outside%20their%20area)). No formal lottery or deferred acceptance algorithm is used; instead, placements are allocated according to the priority criteria and capacity. Private and faith-based schools in Canberra run their own independent admissions, so the coordinated system applies only to public secondary schools.
